<paper id="1524811847"><title>On indefinite databases and the closed world assumption</title><year>1987</year><authors><author org="University of Maryland" id="250356191">Jack Minker</author></authors><n_citation>286</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>10948978</reference><reference>153207633</reference><reference>1487591965</reference><reference>1514729613</reference><reference>1592959421</reference><reference>1593077566</reference><reference>1766062603</reference><reference>1766332311</reference><reference>1996347293</reference><reference>2003287551</reference><reference>2005090804</reference><reference>2021473914</reference><reference>2040326164</reference><reference>2082880188</reference><reference>2105486835</reference><reference>2108911687</reference><reference>2125692076</reference><reference>2155322595</reference><reference>2945259913</reference></references><venue id="1134440762" type="C">Conference on Automated Deduction</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0000066</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.48345">Atomic formula</keyword><keyword weight="0.44675">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.59756">Horn clause</keyword><keyword weight="0.49103">Of the form</keyword><keyword weight="0.4117">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.43961">Minimal model</keyword><keyword weight="0.52426">Closed-world assumption</keyword><keyword weight="0.37291">Database</keyword><keyword weight="0.41602">Mathematics</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A database is said to be indefinite if there is an answer to a query of the form Pa V Pb where neither Pa nor Pb can be derived from the database. Indefinite databases arise where, in general, the data consists of non-Horn clauses. A clause is non-Horn if it is a disjunction of literals in which more than one literal in the clause is positive.</abstract></paper>